  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from a legal source.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the Anti-Money Laundering Law and other relevant regulations. The Chinese government has established a robust legal framework and enforcement mechanisms to combat money laundering activities. Financial institutions and other designated non-financial businesses are required to implement stringent compliance measures, such as customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions to the authorities.\n\nViolations of anti-money laundering laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and criminal prosecution. The Chinese government is committed to upholding the rule of law and maintaining the integrity of its financial system, and it actively cooperates with international efforts to combat money laundering and related financial crimes.",
